## How the maintainer team grows

As participation grows, the sole-maintainer model becomes a bottleneck and a risk. Here's how it scales:

### Phase 1 — Trusted reviewers
When reference data updates outpace the sole maintainer's capacity, or when domain expertise is needed that the maintainer lacks, trusted reviewers are added. A trusted reviewer can review and comment on PRs but cannot merge; they give the maintainer a second pair of eyes for decisions in their domain (e.g., a GST-focused CA reviewing rate changes, a TDS specialist reviewing section updates).

Trusted reviewers are invited by the maintainer. There is no application process; invitations go out when the maintainer knows someone well enough to trust their review and that person has demonstrated both domain expertise and good judgment.

### Phase 2 — Co-maintainers
When the repo is clearly outgrowing a single merger, co-maintainers are added. A co-maintainer can merge PRs within their domain. Decisions that affect the whole repo (spec changes, RFCs, governance changes) still require consensus among maintainers.

Co-maintainers are added by invitation from existing maintainers, with consensus from all existing maintainers. A co-maintainer who becomes inactive for six months is moved to emeritus status and loses merge rights (but keeps credit in the project history).

### Phase 3 — Steering committee
Only if the standard is adopted beyond Bahi and has multiple implementations in active use. A small steering committee (3-5 people) would handle cross-cutting decisions: major spec versions, significant governance changes, conflict resolution. Routine work stays with individual maintainers.

Steering committee formation would itself go through an RFC. It's deliberately left unspecified here because it's hypothetical until participation actually reaches that scale.

